<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
  <dict>
    <!--
      Entitlements for the bundled CPython interpreter (resources/python) and its
      virtualenv (resources/venv).

      Only BASE Python deps are baked into the venv at build time; optional source
      connectors (e.g. psycopg2 for PostgreSQL) are installed on demand at runtime
      via `uv sync --group <name>` on the user's machine. Those wheels ship native
      extension modules (.so) that are ad-hoc signed (TeamIdentifier "not set") —
      they were never signed with our Developer ID.

      Under the hardened runtime, macOS library validation refuses to dlopen a
      Mach-O whose Team ID differs from the loading process, which is exactly the
      python3.12 interpreter we sign with our Developer ID. The result is a load
      failure: "mapping process and mapped file (non-platform) have different Team
      IDs", and the connector reports its optional dependency as unavailable even
      after a successful install.

      disable-library-validation lets the interpreter load these runtime-installed
      extension modules. It is permitted for Developer ID notarization. We scope it
      to the Python binaries via forge.config.ts `optionsForFile` so the Electron
      app/helpers keep their stricter defaults.
    -->
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-dyld-environment-variables</key>
    <true/>
  </dict>
</plist>
